<header class="header">
      <h1>Seed Starting Schedule for Short Growing Seasons</h1>
      <p class="tagline">
        A clear method for planning indoor starts and transplant timing.
      </p>
      <p class="lede">
        In shorter climates, frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong> defines the boundary of your usable growing season.
        Because the frost-free window is limited, seed starting schedules must be built around
        typical last frost timing and the amount of heat that can accumulate afterward.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Start With One Anchor Date</h2>

      <p>
        Every spring plan begins with your <strong>average last frost date</strong>,
        calculated at the 50% probability level using 1991–2020 climate normals.
        This date represents the point in a typical year when frost risk declines to roughly even odds.
      </p>

      <p>
        That anchor date becomes the reference point for:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Indoor seed starting windows</li>
        <li>Hardening off periods</li>
        <li>Outdoor transplant timing</li>
        <li>Direct sow windows</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Instead of guessing when to plant, count backward (or forward) from this climate boundary.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you prefer to generate these windows automatically based on your local frost timing,
        use the <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Starting Planner</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>The 3 Planning Windows That Matter</h2>

      <h3>1. Indoor Start Window</h3>
      <p>
        In short growing seasons, warm-season crops often require a 6–10 week indoor head start.
        Counting backward from your typical last frost date ensures seedlings are ready
        when outdoor conditions historically allow safe transplanting.
      </p>

      <p>
        Starting too early can create overgrown plants waiting on cold soil.
        Starting too late reduces the total frost-free and heat accumulation window available for maturity.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Hardening Off Period</h3>
      <p>
        Plan 7–10 days before transplanting to gradually expose seedlings to
        wind, sun, and temperature swings.
      </p>

      <p>
        In shorter climates, shock-related setbacks can reduce early-season growth,
        which compresses the already limited heat accumulation window.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Transplant or Direct Sow Window</h3>
      <p>
        Warm-season crops are typically transplanted after the 32°F frost boundary has passed.
        Cool-season crops may be planted slightly before the last frost date,
        depending on their cold tolerance.
      </p>

      <p>
        Aligning transplant timing with typical frost decline protects early growth
        and preserves as much seasonal development time as possible.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Why This Matters More in Short Growing Seasons</h2>

      <p>
        In long climates, small timing errors may not significantly affect maturity.
        In short climates, every week influences total seasonal heat accumulation.
      </p>

      <p>
        Warm-season crops such as tomatoes and peppers require substantial Growing Degree Days (GDD)
        after transplanting to mature fully.
      </p>

      <p>
        If transplant timing slips too late, the crop may encounter cooling temperatures
        before sufficient heat has accumulated — even if frost has not yet returned.
      </p>

      <p class="fine">
        In constrained climates, indoor timing directly affects total usable heat.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Which Crops Should You Start Indoors?</h2>

      <p><strong>Usually started indoors (short-season advantage):</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Tomatoes</li>
        <li>Peppers</li>
        <li>Broccoli</li>
        <li>Cabbage</li>
        <li>Kale</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Usually direct sown:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Spinach</li>
        <li>Beans</li>
        <li>Carrots</li>
        <li>Radishes</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        In shorter climates, giving warm crops a controlled indoor start
        increases the portion of the season spent accumulating heat outdoors.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cool-season crops, by contrast, often tolerate early planting and may not require indoor head starts.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>The Short-Season Planning Model</h2>

      <p>
        Building a seed starting schedule in a short growing season follows this sequence:
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Last Frost Date → Indoor Start Timing → Transplant Window → Seasonal Heat Accumulation → Crop Maturity</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        When each step aligns with your local climate normals,
        crops have the maximum possible time to develop before first fall frost returns.
      </p>

      <p>
        In short growing seasons, structured planning reduces maturity risk
        and improves harvest reliability in a typical year.
      </p>
    </section>